{"cursor":"39237","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" predictors]] In signal detection theory, a 'receiver operating characteristic'\n ('ROC'), or simply 'ROC curve', is a graphical plot which illustrates the\n performance of a binary classifier system as its discrimination threshold is\n varied. It is created by plotting the fraction of true positives out of the\n positives (TPR = true positive rate) vs. the fraction of false positives out of\n the negatives (FPR = false positive rate), at various threshold settings. TPR\n is also known as sensitivity (also called recall in some fields), and FPR is\n one minus the specificity or true negative rate.\n\nROC analysis provides tools to select possibly optimal models and to discard\nsuboptimal ones independently from (and prior to specifying) the cost context or\nthe class distribution. ROC analysis is related in a direct and natural way to\ncost/benefit analysis of diagnostic decision making. The ROC curve was first\ndeveloped by electrical engineers and radar engineers during World War II for\ndetecting enemy objects in battlefields and was soon introduced to psychology to\naccount for perceptual detection of stimuli. ROC analysis since then has been\nused in medicine, radiology, biometrics, and other areas for many decades and is\nincreasingly used in machine learning and data mining research.\n\nThe ROC is also known as a relative operating characteristic curve, because it\nis a comparison of two operating characteristics (TPR and FPR) as the criterion\nchanges. Swets, John A.;\n[http://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=91082370 Signal detection theory and ROC\nanalysis in psychology and diagnostics : collected papers], Lawrence Erlbaum\nAssociates, Mahwah, NJ, 1996\n","linknr":413,"url":"Receiver_operating_characteristic","recorded":1362583821,"links":44,"instances":["mathematics","tests","classification_context","information_retrieval","mathematics","tests"],"pdf":["http://www.inmet.gov.br/documentos/cu